I agree as well.  Unstandardized QS does not affect understandability.  
So if that is the case then it should not be a problem for people to 
write as they speak.  I am a U.S. citizen, and in the mid 70s I 
corresponded with a man in New Zealand in QS.  I had no difficulty in 
understanding his QS.  I think the drive toward standardizing QS arises 
out of the same human desire for uniformity that sent TO down the wrong 
path centuries ago.


Paige Gabhart


On 2/21/2013 9:01 AM, moira_ob wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I so agree with Nash. I write QS as I speak - and I read other&#39;s 
&gt; writing in their speech with their pronunciation. It does not detract 
&gt; from my understanding of what they are writing, rather it gives the 
&gt; right colour to their &quot;speech&quot;.
&gt;
&gt; Long live unstandardised QS.
&gt;
&gt; Moira
&gt;
&gt; Moira O&#39;Brien LIPF
&gt; www.corkinternationalradio.com
&gt;
&gt; --- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com 
&gt; &lt;mailto:Read_Alphabet%40yahoogroups.com&gt;, &quot;raghaillaigh&quot; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I really like QS. I use it to write my journal.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; But it can either be phonetic or it can be standardized � it 
&gt; cannot be both. To standardize QS is to start making the same mistake 
&gt; that brought modern English spelling to the state it&#39;s in. Once 
&gt; writing is divorced from pronunciation, then the writing is about 
&gt; something else. For example,the three day gathering whose name is 
&gt; pronounced &quot;wick�d fair&quot; is written &quot;Wicked Faire&quot;. Here, spelling 
&gt; is used to say something non-linguistic about the gathering.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; There is a quicker solution to the spelling problem than adopting 
&gt; QS: it&#39;s called &quot;spelling pronunciation&quot;. That&#39;s where the T 
&gt; pronounced in &quot;often&quot; comes from. It&#39;s why I make a distinction 
&gt; between eh-ffect and ae-ffect, wailing and whaling. In other words, it 
&gt; is by forcing a correspondence between writing and pronunciation and 
&gt; turn TO into a phonetic system.
&gt; &gt; Vin
&gt; &gt; --- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com 
&gt; &lt;mailto:Read_Alphabet%40yahoogroups.com&gt;, John Cowan wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; fern.wing169 scripsit:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; No-- &#39;wh&#39; isn&#39;t always used before why. How you write it is supposed
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; to depend on *your* accent. British speakers would write their words
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; differently than, say, someone from ohio. You should write the
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; lettering the way that you phonetically pronounce it when you speak.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Just be aware that not everyone adopts that point of view. When 
&gt; writing
&gt; &gt; &gt; for yourself only, you can do whatever you like, of course. But it&#39;s
&gt; &gt; &gt; clear that Read designed his script so that everyone would write the
&gt; &gt; &gt; same way, which is why he insists that words like START are 
&gt; written with
&gt; &gt; &gt; Are, not with Ah, even though almost everybody outside North America
&gt; &gt; &gt; pronounces them the same way.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Also, in most cases you don&#39;t have to distinguish awe from ah from
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &quot;ox&quot;. Those three symbols look visually similar for a reason. 
&gt; It&#39;s so
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; that when you&#39;re writing you can just sort of blur them together and
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; people will still know how to pronounce what you wrote.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Every English-speaker outside of North America makes a three-way
&gt; &gt; &gt; distinction, and about 50% of the people in the U.S. make a two-way
&gt; &gt; &gt; distinction: for most of us, Ox = Ah, but in Eastern New England 
&gt; Ox = Awe.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
